03634nam a22005175i 9780822394846DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223948467 a10.1515/97808223948462doi  a(DE-B1597)552674  a(OCoLC)1125512766  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aWest, Paige, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Modern Production to Imagined Primitive :bThe Social World of Coffee from Papua New Guinea /cPaige West. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b35 photographs, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTABLES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. The World of Coffee from Papua New Guinea -- t2. Neoliberal Coffee -- t3. Historic Coffee -- t4. Village Coffee -- t5. Relational Coffee -- t6. National Coffee -- t7. International Coffee -- t8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this vivid ethnography, Paige West tracks coffee as it moves from producers in Papua New Guinea to consumers around the world. She illuminates the social lives of the people who produce coffee, and those who process, distribute, market, and consume it. The Gimi peoples, who grow coffee in Papua New Guinea's highlands, are eager to expand their business and social relationships with the buyers who come to their highland villages, as well as with the people working in Goroka, where much of Papua New Guinea's coffee is processed; at the port of Lae, where it is exported; and in Hamburg, Sydney, and London, where it is distributed and consumed. This rich social world is disrupted by neoliberal development strategies, which impose prescriptive regimes of governmentality that are often at odds with Melanesian ways of being in, and relating to, the world. The Gimi are misrepresented in the specialty coffee market, which relies on images of primitivity and poverty to sell coffee. By implying that the "backwardness" of Papua New Guineans impedes economic development, these images obscure the structural relations and global political economy that actually cause poverty in Papua New Guinea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCoffee industryzPapua New Guinea. 0aCoffeexSocial aspectszPapua New Guinea. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394846zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394846.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles